Dear Madam Gov and Representatives:

Ref H918 - the Coastal Game Fish Act - I and many others have received a message from a local Guide, telling of flounder nets set across prime Red Drum and Speckled Trout waters, where there have been NO flounder caught over the minmum size limit for years, but where the Red Drum bycatch lay dead or drying in the nets.

Yes, these nets were set in-season, and the legality of the placement or attendance is not the point  here, although MF told the Guide there was virtually nothing they could do about the illegal out-of-season waste.  The point is, that the mess the Legislature has made of the fishing regulations, coupled with the highly questionable if not illegal activities of a certain number of commercial fisherman WHO KNOW THEY CAN GET AWAY WITH IT, are going to eventually eliminate the stock of Red Drum and Speckled Trout just as the commercial crowd pretty much eliminated the Grey trout stocks in our waters because NO ONE WOULD STAND UP TO THE COMMERCIAL MONEY to declare those fish as Game Fish. 
The Greys are gone, but now with H918 you at least have a chance to save the Red Drum and the Speckled Trout as Game Fish.

Hopefully, you will pass it.  We know that the 400,000 recreational fishermen in our State don't represent the money, nor the political "pull" that the commercial groups have, but there comes a time when the very existence of the thing they want to kill till it's totally gone and we want to try to preserve in some sort of balance for all of us in the future is at hand.  This is that time.

Hopefully, you will understand that it's not "us against them" - it's about the fish.  When these fish are gone because of the commercial attacks on the stocks, whether was a money crop or as waste, then what will the commercial groups go after next?  There has to be some point where you say "enough".

Do you care?  Can you overcome the commercial money and political influence long enough to do this?

