Goveror Perdue,

I was writing as a concerned angler and responsible citizen. I have made my career as a recreational fishing guide, and I have seen many changes in the fishing industry since I became a full-time fishing guide in 1996.
One of the most important changes that has been made is a big-bold leap towards conservation and realization that our resources are renewable if they are cared for in the proper manner; however, if cared for improperly or not cared for at all these resources that we all rely on so much will not sustain themselves forever.
I graduated from Appalachian State University with a degree in Recreation Management, and during my college days I did a term paper on the recreational value of a fish versus the commercial value of a fish. And now in my career after I have taken nearly 2000 anglers fishing in NC and TN I realize the true value of the resources. I have recently started in new business located in east Tennessee worth in the neighborhood of $ 2 million, and we depend upon the sustainability of our wild resources for the success of that business.
I find it very odd that NC is one of the premier saltwater fishing states in this country and we do so little to protect our resources. I just read in the current issue of Wildlife in NC that NC is in the top five coastal recreational fishing states in realtion to economic value. Coastal recreational fishing generates $ 2 billion for this state while Florida ( #1 ) generates $16.7 billion. There is no arguing that Florida has more coastline and a more storied tradition in regards to coastal angling, but they were also one of the first states to proactively protect their marine resources with the Inshore Net Ban and the Longlining Ban. Why can't NC follow in Florida's footsteps and become one of the leaders in marine conservation? Be assured if we could do that, we would start to follow in their footsteps in relation to the massive recreational fishing industry that exist in Florida. 
Thank you for your time and your consideration.


