Dear Representatives,
My name is Edmund H McGovern Jr and I am emailing you with my concerns about Bill H918. I have been a commercial fisherman for more than 25 years as well as run a local seafood market in the area for just as long. I have fished these waters along with several other commercial fisherman in the area for many years and am appalled that anyone would try to regulate these fish in a time such as this. I agree that we should be mindful of abusing our natural resources, but having dealt with both species of these fish for several years, i don't really see  the need for more regulation at the moment. I have personally witnessed more recreational fishermen than ever come into our local waters and fish for the 'Giant Puppydrum' that usually run in the late summer to early fall. Granted these fish are usually thrown back, there have been more people than ever trying to partake in catching them. Along the same lines come the commercial fishermen, who don't fish out of sport, but out of necessity. These men are out there fishing for their families in order to make a means to put food on the table, and are hardly damaging the ecosystem. With only around $800,000 in total revenue from these fish combined, it seems trivial to think that they are being over fished. If anything, the over fishing comes from the Recreational guys who fail to follow the rules and regulations set out for them, after all, their families aren't depending on that days catch to support them, its just 'for the fun of it'. Not to mention the fact that our economy is in a down swing, now why would we want to put restrictions on a very viable means of income for some people. Commercial fishing doesn't take very much money to start up and can be a very effective tool to add additional support to someones income. Also, we as commercial fishermen cannot stop where or how the fish run, if they get caught in our nets over night, most of them are dead by morning. So instead of being able to sell these fish, we are forced to throw them back and lose not only the life of that particular fish, but the income it could have provided, or the belly it could have filled up for someones family. We also need to look closely at the information that was given about the over fishing of these 2 species. Why should we be compared to Florida in how much was brought in from the recreational side? Florida has one of the highest foreclosure rates in the nation, due in large part to people over extending on their means of living, which could very well include hobbies and sports, such as fishing. Not to mention the fact that Florida is an area high in retirees and people who live lavish lifestyles, they are more equipped financially to spend money on a hobby, up here in North Carolina, you don't find that many wealthy people along our coast. We live by modest means, and shouldn't have yet another work opportunity snatched away from us, there has been enough job loss in the area, so why don't we create some jobs for a change? I personally believe that we have become just like Wall Street, where the ones who get punished are the ones who actually have to work for a living, while all along, the ones who don't depend on the resources, reap all of the benefits.
Please think twice before you vote on this Bill, it is a matter of someone's job versus another man's hobby.
Sincerely,
Ed McGovern Jr.
Commercial Fisherman
Owner of Tryon Palace Seafood

